00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:09.200
the totals, what's happening to those totals? And&nbsp;
at this stage here, we see that this is probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:14.440
telling us something. This is suggesting to us,&nbsp;
because let's say we know that this diverges, it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:19.640
suggesting to us that this is going to diverge&nbsp;
as well, right? It would be rather strange if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:19.640 --> 00:19:28.240
this thing here converged to something like 13.5&nbsp;
and this diverged. So that's telling us something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.240 --> 00:19:33.960
about the prime numbers already. Actually, it's&nbsp;
telling us something about how sparse they are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:42.600
or how not sparse they are. The fact that this&nbsp;
product presumably diverges is giving us some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:49.920
kind of information about the large scale growth&nbsp;
of prime numbers, so in a large scale kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.920 --> 00:19:58.640
way. So let's do one more variant which moves us&nbsp;
quite close to the Euler product story, but also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:05.120
brings suddenly into being this idea that&nbsp;
actually we're doing something non-trivial here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:11.520
that we're actually touching base with some subtle&nbsp;
and actually rather delicate mathematics just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.520 --> 00:20:19.480
from this sort of elementary arithmetic with&nbsp;
these boxes and carrots and forming sums. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:19.480 --> 00:20:23.520
the variant is that we're going to replace all&nbsp;
numbers in the fundamental identity with their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:30.680
squared reciprocals, not their squares, not their&nbsp;
reciprocals, but the squares of their reciprocals,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:37.720
or the reciprocals of their squares, same thing.&nbsp;
So looking at the first box with powers of two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:42.760
we're taking all those powers of two&nbsp;
and raising them to the minus 2 power,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:47.680
and same thing with the box of powers of&nbsp;
three, etc. And on the right-hand side, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:54.960
we're getting the box consisting of all the square&nbsp;
reciprocals of the natural numbers. Now this first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:54.960 --> 00:20:59.520
box here, we can write it as one, this one here&nbsp;
is 1 over 2², this one is 1 over 2²², this one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:07.640
is 1 over 2²³. We do the same thing as before,&nbsp;
always interchange the order of the powers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.640 --> 00:21:13.000
that makes this also into a geometric series. Same&nbsp;
thing with this one, and also with the next one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:20.080
etc. Here the ratio is 1 over 2². Here the ratio&nbsp;
is 1 over 3². The next one, the ratio 1 over 5²,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:28.520
etc. And on the right-hand side, the M set&nbsp;
of reciprocals of squares of natural numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.560 --> 00:21:36.840
Now let's see what happens when we apply S, and&nbsp;
suddenly something really interesting comes into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:44.560
focus. So here I've copied what we've just&nbsp;
obtained: powers of two reciprocal squares,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:48.800
powers of three reciprocal squares, powers&nbsp;
of five reciprocal squares, etc., carrotting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:54.440
them all together. And here is the M set of the&nbsp;
reciprocal squares of the natural numbers. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:54.440 --> 00:22:01.280
each of these inside is a geometric series. When&nbsp;
we apply our summation operator, so we take the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:11.000
sum of all these guys: first term one, ratio 1&nbsp;
over 2². So we get 1/1 - 1 over 2². The next one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:23.120
first term one, ratio 1 over 3². So we get 1 over&nbsp;
1 - 1 over 3² * 1 over 1 - 1/5², etc. And on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.120 --> 00:22:32.200
right-hand side, the sum of the reciprocals&nbsp;
of the squares of the natural numbers. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:37.560
what does this look like in practice? Well, this&nbsp;
is 3/4. Over here, when we take the reciprocal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:37.560 --> 00:22:51.080
we get 4/3. Here we have 1 - 1/9, so that's 8/9.&nbsp;
Reciprocal 9/8. Over here, 5² is 25 - 1 is 24,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:51.080 --> 00:22:58.800
so we get 25/24. Next one is 7, we get&nbsp;
49/48, and so on. So now we have the square&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:07.320
of the primes in the numerators and one less&nbsp;
than each of those in the denominator. Now the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:12.800
right-hand side, however, is very different from&nbsp;
the previous one because there's a square there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:12.800 --> 00:23:21.680
and Euler famously realized that this thing sums&nbsp;
not to infinity, doesn't go on and on. It actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:29.840
sums to something that he was able to identify in&nbsp;
terms of pi, famously pi²/6. So that's certainly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:29.840 --> 00:23:37.720
one of Euler's great remarkable formulas which&nbsp;
made a big impression on everyone. It is still&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:43.360
a remarkable kind of thing, even though strictly&nbsp;
speaking, you know, what is pi? Well, we don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.360 --> 00:23:47.400
really know. And actually, this sum strictly&nbsp;
speaking also, it doesn't really work, but there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:51.960
something going on here. Okay, definitely there's&nbsp;
something going on here, something like magic. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:58.600
now what we have is from this box arithmetic point&nbsp;
of view, some kind of identity like this, that for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.600 --> 00:24:03.200
assuming Euler's result, and we suppose we have&nbsp;
some approximate meaning to this, it means that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:10.800
the product of these squared primes divided by&nbsp;
the one less than them, that that is very likely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:17.520
heading towards something actually reasonably&nbsp;
concrete. It's like a region on the number line,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:17.520 --> 00:24:23.600
maybe not exactly a point, but some kind of object&nbsp;
on the number line. So this is now interesting and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:28.600
it's decidedly different from the previous one&nbsp;
that we had where we were just looking at product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:28.600 --> 00:24:36.160
of primes over primes minus one. Great, so&nbsp;
now we actually can make a calculation. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.160 --> 00:24:46.280
let's choose the first primes up to 100. So 2²,&nbsp;
3², 5², 7², and all the numbers less than those,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:46.280 --> 00:24:58.760
11², 13², 17², all the way up to 79², 83², 89²,&nbsp;
97². The last prime is 100. Okay, so that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:05.760
an initial sequence of the left-hand side of&nbsp;
what we were obtaining. And this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:11.160
okay, it's a rational number and we can&nbsp;
approximate what it is numerically. My&nbsp;&nbsp;

